SIMPLE: circlet
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Circlet
<hw>Cir"clet</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A little
circle; esp., an ornament for the person, having the form of a circle;
that which encircles, as a ring, a bracelet, or a headband.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Her fair locks in <qex>circlet</qex> be enrolled.</q>
<rj><qau>Spenser.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A round body; an orb.</def>
<rj><au>Pope.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Fairest of stars . . . that crown'st the smiling morn⟦br⟧
With thy bright <qex>circlet</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A circular piece of wood put under a dish at
table.</def> <mark>[Prov. Eng.]</mark> <rj><au>Halliwell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Circocele</ent>⟦br⟧
